The AVE PLUS II Project aims to promote the mobility of learners for learning purposes, as well as meeting the needs identified in the Ave Region. It involves a consortium of 13 schools: Didáxis Cooperativa de Ensino ; Cenatex – Escola Profissional; Escola Secundária Martins Sarmento; Agrupamento de Escolas Gonçalo Sampaio; Externato de S. Miguel de Refojos; Agrupamento de Escolas Camilo Castelo Branco e OFICINA Escola Profissional do Instituto Nun'Alvres; Escola Profissional Cisave AE Francisco de Holanda, AE Santos Simões, AE Fafe, Escola Profissional Bento de Jesus Graça, AE Padre Benjamim Salgado.
Education, Training and Promotion of working experiences are crucial for the development of the Ave region. By Knowing the advantages of the ERASMUS + programme to  foster  exchange,  cooperation  and  mobility between  education  and  professional  training  systems and its contribution to the social and professional development of their participants, CIM do Ave presents this proposal.
 The main aim is to meet the needs and gaps of the Region and improve the performance, quality and attractiveness of education and professional training in Europe, while at the same time encouraging the use of various professional training opportunities in the context of lifelong learning.
Main Aims: 
•  Promote work experiences with new training opportunities for the acquisition of specific professional skills;
•  Increasing the employability of young people in the labour market that is  increasingly global and competitive;
•  Improve the relationship between training and labour market;
•  Increase the level of personal and professional development of the participants;
• Promote the international partnership networks;
•  Strengthen the quality of school organization and promote the visibility of the schools;;
•  Promote the Vocational Education as an alternative quality;
• encourage innovation and entrepreneurship, 
• Contribute to a European awareness that leads to an active and participatory citizenship
The present project is addressed to vocational trainees divided equal in number by each consortium of schools. Thus, each school will send 8 trainees from different professional training courses. This project aims to give an opportunity for participants with vocational training of performing an international internship; and to 20 professionals (teachers and staff) in order to support their personal and professional development to improve future activities.
By participating in this project, the participants will achieve the following objectives: a) consolidate knowledge; b) acquire new skills and become more competitive in the labour market access; c) learn or improve a new language; d) get in touch with the labour market; e) the acquisition of new forms of communication, relationship with other cultures, and the integration on the real European common market. 
At the end of the project we expect to have been able to build a partnership that does not  finishes with the end of the project, but that is maintained with mutual benefits of networking by sharing knowledge, experiences, needs and goals. Our second goal is to help the recognition of Europe as a space of all citizens, with more mobility on employment and training. Finally, we intend to help participants achieving their career goals, as well as a deep consciousness that mobility experiences are increasingly needed to be competitive in the labour market.
We believe that this project will be an asset to the plan of activities of the CIM do AVE, particularly regarding to the Plan for the Inclusive Growth of the AVE and Vocational Training. It will provide to young people and to staff of the region important solutions to their real training needs and it will be a complement to their experience to enable them to face the labour market with more optimistic perspectives.
The program will be carried during 24 months and the mobility period for each trainee will be 3 months. The Participants will have preparation before the departure, cultural preparation , socio-cultural activities, internships in selected companies according to each participant's profile, monitoring, mentoring and continuous evaluation throughout the program and collection and evaluation of the results obtained and the labour integration rate.

The project is a proposal from an italian mobility Consortium, which involves partners (VET secondary level schools, VET tertiary level organisations, enterprises) caming from Emilia Romagna region and which unsigned a network agreement to build the VET Hub named "POLO TECNICO-PROFESSIONALE PER LA FILIERA MECCANICA FORNOVO DI TARO (PR)", that is a permanent system of sharing resources to organize learning sector-specific activities for mechanical-automotive (especially motor sport). These partners recognise mobility activities in VET for staff and learners in Erasmus + as perfect progression and enhancement of their network agenda, already oriented to answer to the technical competences' needs of the labour market.

Aims of the projects are provision, implementation and follow up of these main mobility activities:

- Staff mobility of VET schools (24 partecipants staying abroad over 7 days) for a training period in VET organisations and/or enterprises (work place, job shadowing, observation), aiming to their professional development towards work-based learning's planning, in order to assess the specific learning power inside the work place, to direct this power for learners' professional qualification and to certify learning results linked to professional standards (particularly Emilia Romagna Region's Qualification System), also to recognize and to transfer credits applying national/european systems (ECVET);

- Learners' mobility of students coming from sending VET schools (48 partecipants and 6 partecipants with special needs in addiction, staying abroad over 35 days,) for traineeships in VET organisations and placement in enterprises belonging to mechanical-automotive sector (especially motor sport), with the aim to develop task-related skills and competencies in mechanical design and production and other linguistic (technical english or language of the country) and/or intercultural skills and competencies, needed for their legitimate peripheral partecipation to communities of practice inside the workplace and also generally needed for their cultural european citizenship;

- Recent graduates' mobility within 1 year of their coming out from sending VET schools (24 partecipants staying abroad over 63 days), for traineeships in enterprises belonging to mechanical-automotive sector (especially motor sport) or in other relevant VET organisations, with the aim to develop task-related skills and competencies in mechanical design and production and other linguistic (technical english or language of the country) and/or intercultural skills and competencies, needed for their working and organisational socialisation and also generally needed for their cultural european citizenship.

At the end of the project, expected impacts on these target groups are: a) professional development of Staff towards structured implementation of mobility and work-based learning activity into pedagogical framework to achieve secondary or tertiary level VET qualifications; b) learners' first working socialisation to international communities of practice by which mechanical-automotive sector (especially motor sport) is characterized and development by learners of specific linguistic and intercultural skills needed for european citizenship. For the organisations involved in the project, expected longterm impacts are the promotion (and their active partecipation) of a VET and continuos training system in Europe, strictly connected with international mechanical-automotive sector (especially motor sport).

The recent experience with ocean wave energy have revealed issues with reliability of technical components, survivability, high development costs and risks, long time to market, as well as industrial scalability of proposed and tested technologies. However the potential of wave energy is vast, and also positive conclusions have been drawn, in particular that wave energy is generally technically feasible. 
Having substantial insight into successes and drawbacks in past developments and existing concepts, the promoters have identified ‘breakthrough features’ that address the above mentioned obstacles, i.e. components, systems and processes, as well as the respective IP. These breakthroughs are applied to two wave concepts, the OWC and the Symphony, under development by members of the consortium. The following main avenues have been identified:

 1. Survivability breakthrough via device submergence under storm conditions;
 2. O&M (operation and maintenance) breakthrough via continuous submergence and adaption of components and strategies;
 3. PTO breakthrough via dielectric membrane alternatives to the “classical” electro-mechanical power take-off equipment;
 4. Array breakthrough via sharing of mooring and electrical connections between nearby devices, as well as integral approach to device interaction and compact aggregates;

WETFEET addressees Low-carbon Energies specific challenges by targeting a set of breakthroughs for wave energy technology, an infant clean energy technology with vast potential. 

The breakthrough features of WETFEET are developed and tested on the platform of two specific converter types (OWC and Symphony) with near-term commercial interest, and a large part of the results can make a general contribution to the sector, being implemented in other technologies.

There will be 28 participants in this project (school inspectors , Gendarmerie officers, psychologists and specialist from "Save the Children" NGO, all having also competences of  trainers):
- 13 School Inspectors;
- 6 representatives of the Inspectorate of Gendarmerie- Arges County , members of The Department for Prevention and Fight against Crimes;
-5 specialists experienced in this topic, from the NGO-Save the Children, Arges branch;
-4 school psychologists from the    Arges county .
These participants selection meet objective criteria, directly connected with the aims of the project. 
We consider that it is important to mention that this target group has been and so will be a constant working group in the Arges county. 

 The identified need is that the main responsible institutions lack the updated knowledge regarding the management of violence phenomenon in the educational environment.  The direct effects of this reflect over their capacity of dealing this phenomenon by working side by side with other counterparts and over their skills in transferring their own experience to the direct beneficiaries. 
From our previous analysis of the problem, the partners in this project have concluded the following causes: the lack of specialised training at the national level in a field quite new for the Romanian specialists, that of the management of violence phenomenon in the educational environment; the lack of experience on how was this problem successfully  approached by others; they don't master adapted working methods to the different target groups they work with: grown-ups and students and each one of these groups are also divided into multiple categories, for example teachers, managers, parents with different levels of education but also officials from various public institutions, etc. 

Therefore, the aim of the project is to improve the professional stakeholders' competences on violence phenomenon management in the educational environment. The OBJECTIVES are:
1. to increase the quality of their professional activity for the educational institutions in the county and other counterparts ( state and public institutions);
2. to improve their competences;
3.  to gain through job-shadowing a coordinated and common professional improving experience to all the representatives of the institutions involved in the management of violence phenomenon in the educational environment (in other words, each one of the participants might have had or can have other trainings separately/individualy, but for this problem they have worked and will work together in the future years, so the positive results can come from the way they cooperate and transfer their knowledge, so their knowledge and skills need to be not only updated but also coordinated and this can happen by gaining the same experiences under similar influences);
4. to ensure international experience with the aim of learning (or "how have the others dealt with this problem").

  At  the end of the job-shadowing experience, they will be significantly more efficient in their professional activity. The will have international experience  which will add also credibility to their future activity in the field of educational environment related to conflict potential and violence management. They will be able to bring positive influence among the educational institutions in the Arges county (school managers, teachers, Administration Councils,community, etc) by mastering common knowledge and updated working methods with different target groups and for different beneficiaries. 

The mobilities will take place in UK, out of the reasons exposed before, related both with this country's experience in this area and with the receiving organisation's background, in 4 stages (flux) starting with September 2014 to May 2015, involving also meetings with counterparts from UK and in various institutions similar with those we are working with, public and educational (County Hall, centers of education, schools, NGO's, etc). There will be monitoring and evaluation during the flux and at the end of it. It is a comprehensive procedure, in order to achieve the participants objectives which will lead to the final certificate. 
Of course, everything will be disseminated according to a realistic but efficient plan (more information on this in H2.2. -Dissemination).
